#ProtectAbortionAccess did you know 8 in 10 Americans support access to legal abortion? That’s right, We’re the majority. 
Feminist Platform Social Justice Curator @aishabburrowes in community and conversation with NARAL @prochoiceamerica and @annie_wu_22 ➡️ Watch & Listen
 ✅ Learn how to continue taking action
✅ what does NARAL do ✅ about the fundraiser & how NARAL will use the donations ✅ combat disinformation ✅ why we need (WHPA) The Women’s Health Protection Act

📞Call your senators and representatives and tell them to support reproductive freedom and pass WHPA: 202-224-3121 (Capitol switchboard will connect you to the office you request)

💜Visit prochoiceamerica.org to get involved in NARAL and learn more.

‼️If you are pregnant, there are resources and people fighting for you. Visit needabortion.org to get the support in getting services and funds you need.

🙏Thank you to the Feminist community for donating 🎉  See #LinkinBio to continue supporting reproductive justice in the U.S.

#FeministPartner @chellaman’s latest project, “Big Deaf” continues to push the boundaries of what it means to be accessible, inclusive, and equal in this world. ➡️ See more at @whatthefuckisthischella.

“Unfortunately the continuum of disability is rarely taught or acknowledged leaving stereotypes as the only outline non-disabled individuals have of disability. With 15% of the world’s population being disabled, the individuality of our community should come at no surprise…” 💭 @chellaman

In this project, @chellaman reflect’s on his own deaf identity to navigate the reality of the continuum of identity. You can discover the perpetual release of “Big Deaf”  at @whatthefuckisthischella ✨

“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

Fat is not a bad word or insult 📣 by @meggarrodart (posted with consent)

“I used to be terrified of the word “fat”.
It was the word that my bullies used to hurt me, to me it used to mean I was ugly and worthless. I used to try everything I could not to be “fat”.

“I know now that fat doesn’t mean any of those things.”
“Fat is simply a descriptive word. It has no relevance to my beauty or worthiness.”
“I will happily call myself fat and beautiful 🥰”

I AM FAT AND PROUD💓✨

Stop telling us to smile. 💭 by @cutecatcalls “In 2015 they told Serena to smile. In 2017 they told Simone to smile. Here we are in 2021 and there are telling Emma Raducanu to smile. 🙃” (posted with consent)
.
“It’s sadly a tale as old as time to tell women, especially women of colour to smile, which is why it’s no surprise that these comments were aimed at two Black women and one mixed race woman. The same old story to be more palatable, pleasing and pretty. To not be the angry Black woman. To not be the resting bitch face. To not be the ungrateful girl.”
.
“The years may have passed, but the response is still the same, women don’t owe you shit.”
.
“Whilst on the topic, if you don’t already follow @stoptellingwomentosmile an art series by Tatyana Fazlalizadeh I encourage you to! The work attempts to address gender based street harassment by placing drawn portraits of women, composed with captions that speak directly to offenders, outside in public spaces.”
.

6 Tweets: by @migrantscribble (posted with consent)

1: For Latinx Heritage month, who is talking about descendants of Japanese Latinxs whose countries of births put them on boats & shipped them to the US to be interned. Once released, some went back to Latin America, some became undocumented, & others fled to Japan?

2: For Latinx Heritage month, who is talking about the descendants of enslaved Black people in South America who fled to the Caribbean islands and are no longer considered to be “Latinx” although their genealogical family tree is primarily in the connected South American countries?

3: For Latinx Heritage month, who is talking about the descendants of Chinese indentured servants in Latin America, specifically Cuba, a landscape that in the 1800’s had about 100,000 Chinese forced laborers in the island, many who died in sugar plantations?

4: For Latinx Heritage month, who is uplifting the Islas Malvinas, aka the Falkland Islands? The archipelago on the s. most part of South America, now a British territory, with a deep history of Argentina trying to include the landscape into the fabric of Latin America?

5: For Latinx Heritage month, who is speaking about the impact of Haiti not only in the Caribbean but in the Americas at large? Who is doing tributes to Haitian resistance, epistemological approaches to Black freedom, and the radical Haitian imagination?

6: i mean, i guess we can all go to our tweeting racially ambiguous illustrations of brown-ish, tan-ish figures & call that revolutionary love & celebration. #latinxheritagemonth #hispanicheritagemonth

Photo shared by Feminist on September 16, 2021 tagging @gaytimes. May be an image of text that says 'Somehow in 2021, bisexuals are still striving to have our existence acknowledged. Yes, gay rights and bisexual rights often go hand in hand; legalisation of same-sex marriage or allowing same-sex couples to adopt children has benefitted bisexual people, as will the final end of 'conversion therapy'. However, just Secause because we go hand in hand in some areas, it doesn't mean that we still face the exact same challenges.'.

Photo shared by Feminist on September 16, 2021 tagging @gaytimes. May be an image of text that says 'Bi-erasure Bi people are often the forgotten part of the LGBTQ+ community. So many queer experiences end up being labelled lesbian and gay experiences that bi (and many other identities within the community) discourse falls at the wayside. When someone comes out as bi, their identity is often erased according to their gender, too. Bi women are too often accused of attention-seeking when they come out, whereas bi men are frequently seen as going through a phase.'.

Photo shared by Feminist on September 16, 2021 tagging @gaytimes. May be an image of text that says 'Stereotypes Bi people also face a number of negative stereotypes. Years of harmful TV and film representation have contributed to the idea that bi people are greedy, manipulative, incapable of monogamy and unable to make their minds up. Every member of the LGBTQ+ community has been subject to some sweeping statement or stereotype, but those faced by the bi community often contribute to the soaring rates of sexual violence and abuse they face in and out of relationships.'.

node.text:
🎨 by @yourewelcomeclub (posted with consent) “⭐️ It’s Sexual Health week! ⭐️ “Consent” is a big theme this year and I’m all for normalising conversations around consent, proactively speaking up about boundaries and wishes/desires and creating a positive and safe environment to do so.”

“We are all different. This means each of us has different preferences and needs regarding interaction with others. Different boundaries. What’s OK for you might not be OK for someone else. Always ask for consent. Whether it's for giving a hug, holding hands or touching someone else's body (even a shoulder or arm). No means No, and silence doesn't mean Yes. If you forgot to ask consent, you can always take a step back and mention this, for example by saying: 'Oh, I totally forgot to check and ask for consent – was this alright for you? I'm sorry if it wasn't, we can find a way of interaction that feels comfortable for you and I'll try my best to do better in the future.' Consent can be 'sexy' – and more importantly it's necessary. It’s a basic ingredient of safe and respectful human interaction 🧡”

“What does consent mean to you? What would you have liked to learn about consent when you were younger?”
